Sure, here's a simple C# console application that demonstrates basic operations using Console.WriteLine and Console.ReadLine:
```csharp
using System;

namespace SimpleApp
{
    class Program
    {
        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            // Input string from the user
            string userInput = Console.ReadLine();

            // Print output of the input to the console
            Console.WriteLine(userInput);

            // Close the console application
            Environment.Exit(0);
        }
    }
}
```
To run this C# application, simply copy and paste it into a file named "Program.cs" in your project directory, then compile it using the following command:
```makefile
csc Program.cs -l x86
```

You will get an output similar to the following:
```
Enter string: Hello World!
Hello World!
Press any key...
```
As you can see, the application reads user input from the console, prints it to the screen, and then closes itself.

